{
  "id": "ramp-url-maze",
  "kind": "problem",
  "title": "API Maze Crawler",
  "difficulty": "hard",
  "concepts": [
    "API traversal",
    "graph traversal",
    "response parsing",
    "retries",
    "cycle detection"
  ],
  "prompt": "I give you a starting URL and a tiny HTTP-like helper. When you fetch a URL, the response may point you at more URLs. Somewhere in that maze there may be a successful response whose body is exactly `\"congrats\"`.\n\nWrite `find_final_url(start_url, max_retries)`.\n\nYour job is to crawl from `start_url` and return the URL whose response body is `\"congrats\"`. Return `None` if you cannot reach one.\n\nIn a real interview this would probably be an HTTP client or a provided helper. In this app, the Python test harness provides `fetch_url(url)` and backs it with hidden test data.\n\nEach call returns one HTTP-like response object. A response can be:\n\n- `{\"status\": 200, \"body\": \"congrats\"}`: you found the answer; return the URL you just fetched.\n- `{\"status\": 200, \"body\": {\"urls\": [...]}}`: those URLs are the next URLs discovered from this page, in order.\n- `{\"status\": 301, \"location\": \"...\"}` or `{\"status\": 302, \"location\": \"...\"}`: a redirect. Treat the location as the single next URL discovered from this response.\n- `{\"status\": 404}`: the URL is not found; treat it as a dead end.\n- `{\"status\": 503}`: a temporary failure for this URL.\n- Anything malformed or missing the expected fields: treat it as a dead end.\n\nSome URLs are flaky. If a fetch returns status `503`, retry that same URL immediately, up to `max_retries` extra times. For example, if a URL returns `503`, then `503`, then `200` with body `\"congrats\"`, it is reachable when `max_retries` is `2`, but not when `max_retries` is `1`.\n\nRedirects can chain or cycle. A redirect counts like following one discovered URL for closest/tie-breaking purposes. Do not return a redirecting URL unless its own successful body is `\"congrats\"`; follow its `location` and return the eventual URL that produces `\"congrats\"`.\n\nThe maze can contain cycles and duplicate links. Do not get stuck repeatedly processing the same URL. If several successful URLs could lead to `\"congrats\"`, return the one reachable in the fewest number of link hops from `start_url`. If there is still a tie, use the order in which URLs are returned by the API.\n\nThe hidden service behaves like this: each URL has a response transcript. The first time you fetch it, you receive the first response; the second time, the second response; after the transcript runs out, the service keeps returning the last response.\n\nVisible example A:\n\n```python\n# hidden fake service\n{\n  \"http://start\": {\"status\": 200, \"body\": {\"urls\": [\"http://a\", \"http://b\"]}},\n  \"http://a\": {\"status\": 200, \"body\": {\"message\": \"nothing here\"}},\n  \"http://b\": {\"status\": 200, \"body\": \"congrats\"}\n}\n\nfind_final_url(\"http://start\", 2) == \"http://b\"\n```\n\nVisible example B:\n\n```python\n# hidden fake service\n{\n  \"s\": {\"status\": 200, \"body\": {\"urls\": [\"r\"]}},\n  \"r\": [{\"status\": 503}, {\"status\": 503}, {\"status\": 200, \"body\": \"congrats\"}]\n}\n\nfind_final_url(\"s\", 2) == \"r\"\n```\n\nVisible example C:\n\n```python\n# hidden fake service\n{\n  \"s\": {\"status\": 200, \"body\": {\"urls\": [\"old\"]}},\n  \"old\": {\"status\": 302, \"location\": \"new\"},\n  \"new\": {\"status\": 200, \"body\": \"congrats\"}\n}\n\nfind_final_url(\"s\", 2) == \"new\"\n```\n\nYou do not need real network access, sleeps, exponential backoff, threads, or async code. Focus on the crawling logic, retry boundary, response parsing, redirects, and cycle safety.",
  "signature": {
    "name": "findFinalUrl",
    "inputs": [
      {
        "name": "start_url",
        "type": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      {
        "name": "max_retries",
        "type": {
          "type": "number"
        }
      }
    ],
    "output": {
      "type": "string",
      "nullable": true
    }
  },
  "tests": [
